  "text": "Notably, pharmacological manipulations that augment dopaminergic function can alter RSFC within the mesocorticolimbic system. For example, methylphenidate administration, which would augment striatal dopaminergic activity, increases connectivity in corticolimbic and corticocortical circuits but reduces connectivity between the ventral striatum and putamen in cocaine users. [CITATION_1] In healthy control subjects, connectivity between the midbrain and default mode network is greater in participants receiving L-dopa than in those receiving placebo or haloperidol. [CITATION_2] Another study shows that amphetamine-induced striatal dopamine release was positively associated with connectivity within the cortico-striatal-thalamic network in control subjects and in recreational amphetamine users (average of 40 occasions of use); however, striatal D2-type BP ND was not associated with changes in striatal RSFC in either group. [CITATION_3] These results are consistent with the lack of correlation between striatal BP ND and RSFC in healthy controls reported here. However, the absence of a relationship in recreational amphetamine users, despite the negative association of striatal D2-type BP ND with mesocorticolimbic RSFC in methamphetamine-dependent individuals, may reflect a difference between occasional and prolonged stimulant abuse.",
